Potui, sc. ‘est' This predicative dative, expressing that which a thing or person serves as, or occasions, is com- mon in Tacitus, most frequently in forms in ‘ui,' as ‘victui,' ‘vestitui’ (c. 46, 3), ‘derisui’ (Agr. 39, ag, ‘inrisui' (H. 1. 7, 5), ‘indutui' (A. 1 . 4, ο), ‘obtentui' (H. 1. 49, 6, &c.), ‘ostentui’ (A. 15. 64, 2, &c.).

frumento, probably for the specific term ‘tritico’ (wheat); but it has been doubted whether the Germans then had it. Mead from honey seems to have been known to all Aryan speaking peoples (T aylor, 170) , and intoxicating driuk from grain was known to many nations and had many nomes, as ‘zy- thum’ in Egypt, ‘caelia' and ‘cerea’ in Spain, ‘cervesia’ in Gaul, &a (Plin. aa. 25, 82,164). The old forms of the words ‘ beer' and ‘ale’ may be native German, but their claim is questioned. ‘Barleywine’ was the common drink of the Kelts (Garris) as late as the time of Julian, whose epigram upon it is pre- served (Anth. Pal. ix. 368; see also Mommsen, Hist. v. Ε. T. ’1 108).
